  "text": "Django's CharField max_length validation is implemented across multiple layers:\n\n**1. Field-Level Validation (django/db/models/fields/__init__.py):**\n- The base `Field` class defines `max_length` attribute in `__init__()` at line 215 and validates choices against max_length in `_check_choices()` at line 345-370\n- The `CharField` class extends Field and performs max_length validation in two ways:\n  - `_check_max_length_attribute()` (line 1226-1254) checks that max_length is defined, is an integer, and is positive\n  - `__init__()` (line 1205-1209) adds a `MaxLengthValidator` to the field's validators\n  - `deconstruct()` (line 570-646) serializes max_length for migration detection\n\n**2. Form Field Validation (django/forms/fields.py):**\n- The forms `CharField` class (line 275-308) accepts max_length and adds a `MaxLengthValidator` (line 287) to validate input length during form validation\n\n**3. Validator Implementation (django/core/validators.py):**\n- `MaxLengthValidator` class (line 489-503) implements the actual validation logic using `compare()` and `clean()` methods\n\n**4. Database Backend Enforcement:**\n- **MySQL** (django/db/backends/mysql/base.py, line 116): Maps CharField to \"varchar(%(max_length)s)\" and validates in django/db/backends/mysql/validation.py (line 49) that unique CharFields don't exceed 255 characters\n- **PostgreSQL** (django/db/backends/postgresql/base.py, line 86-89): Uses `_get_varchar_column()` function to generate \"varchar(%(max_length)s)\" or \"varchar\" depending on max_length\n- **SQLite** (django/db/backends/sqlite3/base.py, line 43-46): Similar to PostgreSQL with `_get_varchar_column()` function\n- **Oracle** (django/db/backends/oracle/base.py, line 131): Maps CharField to \"NVARCHAR2(%(max_length)s)\"\n- **Base validation** (django/db/backends/base/validation.py, line 13-32): Provides framework for backend-specific field validation via `check_field_type()` method\n\n**5. Migration Auto-Detection (django/db/migrations/autodetector.py):**\n- `MigrationAutodetector.deep_deconstruct()` (line 74-121) recursively deconstructs field objects, including max_length\n- `_generate_altered_fields()` (line 1254-1377) detects field changes by comparing old and new field deconstructed representations (line 1334-1335) and generates `AlterField` operations when max_length changes\n- The comparison at line 1339 (`old_field_dec != new_field_dec`) triggers creation of an `AlterField` operation (line 1366) when max_length differs\n\n**6. Migration Operations (django/db/migrations/operations/fields.py):**\n- `AlterField` class (line 204-263) represents the migration operation that alters a field's database column, including max_length changes, with `database_forwards()` method at line 235-245 executing the actual schema change"
